<subSubSection id="748C08FAFF8C500637F891E001B393FB" pageId="2" pageNumber="67" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3C295B71FF8C500637F891E001B393FB" blockId="2.[151,1437,152,1511]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8C500637F891E0021B93A6" bold="true" box="[199,334,1413,1439]" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is composed of the Latin words 
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8C500634A691E1008493A7" box="[921,977,1412,1438]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">denti</emphasis>
(tooth) and 
<emphasis id="0EE28763FF8C5006336691E0079A93A7" box="[1113,1231,1413,1438]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="67">giganteum</emphasis>
(great), and refers to the huge calcars on posterior margin of scutellum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
